The paper deals with the problem of reconstructing high-dimensional sparse wavelet signals from partial Fourier measurements, which is a topic in signal processing and information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.SP (Signal Processing) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also involves the use of deterministic sampling sets, which is a topic in computational complexity, hence cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is also a possible sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves numerical methods for solving the reconstruction problem, which is a topic in numerical analysis, hence cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) is another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of sparsity in wavelet signals, which is a topic in machine learning and data analysis, hence cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is also a possible sub-category.
